<body/> 
</html> 

<!-- what is html boiler code  -->
Ans html boiler plate code is a basic must tag that has to be write in order to write a 
html document 
<!DOCTYPE html> 
<html> 
<head> 
<meta charset="UTF-8"> 
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-                   
scale=1.0"> 
<title>boiler code</title> 
</head> 
<body> 
<body/> 
</html> 
<!DOCTYPE html>, <html>, <meta>, <head>, and <body> are boilerplate code, you 
write them in every HTML page, even though the main content changes. 

Explanation of each tag in boiler code: 
1. <!DOCTYPE html> ‚Üí Tells the browser this is an HTML5 document. 
2. <html lang="en"> ‚Üí Root element, language is English. 
3. <head> ‚Üí Contains meta information (not shown on page). 
 3.1 <meta charset="UTF-8"> ‚Üí UTF-8 allows us to use all languages + 
emojis directly. 
 3.2 If we used ASCII only, non-English text or emojis wouldn‚Äôt display 
properly. 
 3.3 <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial
scale=1.0"> ‚Üí Makes site responsive on mobile. 
3.4 <title> ‚Üí Title shown on browser tab. 
4. <body> ‚Üí Actual content of the page (what users see). 
<!-- How to Generate boiler code in VS Code  -->
1. Type: exclamation mark(!) it gives emmit abbreviation  
2. Click on emmit abbreviation ‚Üí VS Code will auto-generate the full HTML 
boilerplate.  

